The sudden leakage of clear fluid from the vagina, along with chronic hypertension and missed prenatal appointments, suggests preterm premature rupture of membranes (PPROM). The ferning pattern in the vaginal fluid supports the diagnosis of PPROM. Ascending infection is the most common cause of PPROM. Sexual intercourse in the third trimester is a risk factor for PPROM, but it is not the cause in this case. β-blocker use and alcohol use are not related to PPROM.
